<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<%- include(`${templatePath}/shared2026/head`, {
  headTitle: 'Standardizing Provider-Created Bundles into a Scalable Package System — Vicky Wang',
  headDescription: 'Created a standardized package system providers could adopt, giving BabyQuip a foundation for bundle discovery, legacy migration, and merchandising.',
  headRobots: 'noindex, follow',
  headType: 'article',
  headImage: 'https://vickywang.me/thumbnails/cs_package.png'
}) %>

<body>

  <%- include(`${templatePath}/shared2026/header`, {
    headerVariant: 'detail',
    headerHome: '/worklog',
    headerAvatar: '../../web_images/photo_profile_avatar.png',
    headerLinks: [
      { href: '#problem', label: 'Problem', muted: true },
      { href: '#insight', label: 'Insight', muted: true },
      { href: '#design', label: 'Design', muted: true },
      { href: '#impact', label: 'Impact', muted: true }
    ]
  }) %>

  <section class="cs-hero container cs-section--sm">
    <div class="cs-hero-meta">
      <span class="case-index">&#8470; 5 &middot; Q2 2026 &middot; BabyQuip</span>
      <span class="tag">SUPPLY SIDE &mdash; PARTNER PORTAL</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="cs-h2 cs-h2--display-wide">Standardizing Provider-Created Bundles into a Scalable Package System</h1>
    <p class="cs-hero-sub cs-hero-sub--wide">Turned unstructured provider-created packages into a standardized system BabyQuip could track, expand, and eventually merchandise, while preserving custom packages and migrating existing provider work.</p>

    <div class="cs-divider-grid cs-divider-grid--hero">
      <div>
        <div class="cs-label">INTERNAL PACKAGE TRACKING</div>
        <div class="cs-stat-value--sm">~59% <span class="cs-stat-annotation">opportunity gap</span></div>
        <div class="cs-stat-label">Between package-like demand and actual standard-package bookings</div>
        <div class="cs-stat-note">Internal package tracking at time of measurement &mdash; full breakdown in <a href="#problem" class="cs-inline-link">01 &mdash; Problem</a>.</div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="cs-label">PACKAGE MODEL SHIFT</div>
        <div class="cs-stat-value--sm cs-stat-value--36">Provider-created <span class="accent">&rarr;</span> platform-defined</div>
        <div class="cs-stat-label">Standard package templates &middot; Provider adoption &middot; Legacy migration &middot; Custom packages preserved</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cs-divider-grid cs-divider-grid--tight cs-divider-grid--bleed">
      <div>
        <div class="cs-label">ROLE</div>
        <div class="cs-text">Product UX designer for the package-system redesign</div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="cs-label">SCOPE</div>
        <div class="cs-text">Provider portal package system &middot; Standard package adoption &middot; Legacy migration &middot; Consumer-facing representation</div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="cs-label">COLLABORATORS</div>
        <div class="cs-text">Product design, CTO, engineering, QA, data, and provider operations</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="problem" class="cs-section container">
    <div class="cs-kicker">01 &mdash; PROBLEM</div>
    <h2 class="cs-h2 cs-h2--narrow">Package demand existed, but the package system was too fragmented to merchandise</h2>
    <p class="cs-lead">BabyQuip had packages long before this project, but they were not a structured product system. They worked like custom inventory bundles individual providers created inside their own portals: every package could have a different name, item combination, quantity, and pricing logic. During data migration we even found packages containing a single item, &ldquo;package&rdquo; had no consistent definition across the marketplace.</p>
    <p class="cs-lead">As BabyQuip moved toward gear-first shopping, this became a bigger issue. Customers could browse gear before choosing a provider, but packages were still tied to individual providers &mdash; <strong class="cs-text-emphasis">the system could not reliably know which packages existed until after a provider was selected</strong>.</p>
    <div class="u-mt-md">

      <p class="cs-lead u-mt-sm"><strong class="cs-text-emphasis">BEFORE</strong> &mdash; provider-created bundles, invisible until a shopper opened that provider&rsquo;s shop</p>
      <div class="cs-journey-grid">
        <div class="cs-journey-item">
          <div class="cs-journey-num">1</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-label">Landing</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-quote">Shopper arrives on BabyQuip.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cs-journey-item">
          <div class="cs-journey-num">2</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-label">Shopping</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-quote">Browse individual gear. No packages shown.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cs-journey-item">
          <div class="cs-journey-num">3</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-label">Select provider</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-quote">Choose a provider to rent from.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cs-journey-item cs-journey-item--active">
          <div class="cs-journey-num">4</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-label">Provider shop</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-quote">See only that provider's packages.
            <span class="cs-journey-pill">PACKAGES APPEAR</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cs-journey-item">
          <div class="cs-journey-num">5</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-label">Add &#38; checkout</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-quote">Add items and complete booking.
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="u-mt-md">

      <p class="cs-lead u-mt-sm">
        <strong class="cs-text-emphasis">AFTER</strong> &mdash;
        packages explorable at the shopping step, before provider selection
      </p>
      <div class="cs-journey-grid">
        <div class="cs-journey-item">
          <div class="cs-journey-num">1</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-label">Landing</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-quote">Shopper arrives on BabyQuip.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cs-journey-item  cs-journey-item--active">
          <div class="cs-journey-num">2</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-label">Shopping</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-quote">Browse gear with standard packages available to explore.
            <span class="cs-journey-pill">PACKAGES EXPLORABLE</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cs-journey-item">
          <div class="cs-journey-num">3</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-label">Select provider</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-quote">Choose a provider, already aware of packages.

          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cs-journey-item">
          <div class="cs-journey-num">4</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-label">Provider shop</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-quote">Confirm package and provider details.

          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cs-journey-item">
          <div class="cs-journey-num">5</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-label">Add &#38; checkout</div>
          <div class="cs-journey-quote">Add items and complete booking.

          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
    <h3 class="cs-h3 u-mt-lg">The legacy package model created five problems</h3>
    <div class="cs-breakdown-grid">
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card-lighter-top-line-lighter-top-line">
        <div class="cs-breakdown-tag">A &middot; No shared structure</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">A package could mean almost anything &mdash; a thoughtful crib-and-stroller bundle or a single item. Without a shared definition, packages could not be grouped, compared, or promoted.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card-lighter-top-line-lighter-top-line">
        <div class="cs-breakdown-tag">B &middot; Buried in inventory</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">Packages had no dedicated experience. Creation was unguided for providers, and adoption was hard for the platform to control or scale.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card-lighter-top-line-lighter-top-line">
        <div class="cs-breakdown-tag">C &middot; Invisible before provider selection</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">In gear-first shopping, customers browse items before choosing a provider &mdash; but packages only existed inside provider shops.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card-lighter-top-line-lighter-top-line">
        <div class="cs-breakdown-tag">D &middot; Consumer exposure needed supply safeguards</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">Fulfillment depended on provider participation. Promoting packages too aggressively before supply coverage improved could strand customers on no-availability results.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card-lighter-top-line-lighter-top-line">
        <div class="cs-breakdown-tag">E &middot; Migration needed to preserve provider work</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">Many providers already had custom packages. The new system could not replace them or force manual rebuilds.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cs-callout-box background-white">
      <div class="cs-callout-label">WHAT THE ~59% GAP MEANT &mdash; DEMAND VS. ADOPTION</div>
      <div class="cs-stat-grid">
        <div>
          <div class="cs-stat-grid-value">41,622</div>
          <div class="cs-stat-grid-caption">Orders contained the right product types for a standard package</div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-stat-grid-value">16,992</div>
          <div class="cs-stat-grid-caption">Orders actually booked a standard package, a ~59% gap</div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-stat-grid-value">889 <span class="cs-stat-annotation--xs">of 3,129</span></div>
          <div class="cs-stat-grid-caption">Active providers offered at least one standard package, ~28% adoption</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="cs-footnote-block">This data did not prove the redesign had already increased package rentals, it showed the size of the opportunity and clarified the real constraint: <strong class="cs-text-emphasis">BabyQuip needed a stronger supply-side package system before packages could become reliable consumer-facing merchandising</strong>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="insight" class="cs-section container">
    <div class="cs-kicker">02 &mdash; INSIGHT</div>
    <h2 class="cs-h2 cs-h2--narrow">Not a UI problem, a system ownership problem</h2>
    <p class="cs-lead">As long as packages were fully created by individual providers, BabyQuip could not treat them as a platform-level merchandising object. Packages needed a <strong class="cs-text-emphasis">shared definition controlled by BabyQuip</strong>, while fulfillment remained provider-dependent. Separating package definition from provider fulfillment became the foundation of the new system.</p>

    <div class="cs-compare">
      <div class="cs-compare-cell background-white">
        <div class="cs-callout-label">BEFORE</div>
        <div class="cs-flow-line cs-flow-line--muted">Provider creates package &rarr; package only exists inside that provider&rsquo;s shop</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-compare-cell cs-compare-cell--after">
        <div class="cs-callout-label cs-callout-label--accent">AFTER</div>
        <div class="cs-flow-line">BabyQuip defines package template &rarr; provider adopts it &rarr; system tracks adoption and represents packages earlier in shopping</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="cs-h3 u-mt-lg">Design goals</h3>
    <div class="cs-breakdown-grid">
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card-lighter-top-line">
        <div class="cs-journey-num-dark">1</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">Standardize core package definitions and make adoption easy for providers</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card-lighter-top-line">
        <div class="cs-journey-num-dark">2</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">Preserve provider flexibility through custom packages and migrate existing work</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card-lighter-top-line">
        <div class="cs-journey-num-dark">3</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">Make adoption trackable, and standard packages referenceable before provider selection</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card-lighter-top-line">
        <div class="cs-journey-num-dark">4</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">Avoid over-promoting packages before supply coverage could support reliable fulfillment</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="design" class="cs-section container">
    <div class="cs-kicker">03 &mdash; DESIGN</div>
    <h2 class="cs-h2 cs-h2--narrow">A dual package system: standardized BabyQuip packages plus custom provider packages</h2>
    <p class="cs-lead">Standardized packages gave BabyQuip a controlled structure for names, item categories, and merchandising logic. Custom packages preserved provider flexibility for cases that did not fit the standard model, a hierarchy, not a rigid template.</p>

    <div class="cs-solutions">
      <div>
        <div class="cs-solution-head">
          <h3><span class="cs-solution-num">1 &middot;</span> Standardized BabyQuip package templates</h3>
          <p>Instead of requiring providers to invent every package from scratch, BabyQuip defined standard templates &mdash; a controlled name, required item categories, and expected combinations. Packages became comparable and trackable across the marketplace, with custom packages kept as a flexible secondary path.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="modal-target" data-modal-gallery="solutions">
          <img src="screenshot_package_type.png" alt="x">
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <div class="cs-solution-head">
          <h3><span class="cs-solution-num">2 &middot;</span> A dedicated package area in the provider portal</h3>
          <p>Packages were separated from general inventory management and given their own area &mdash; no longer just another inventory subtype. The experience prioritized standardized packages first, with custom package creation available as a secondary action.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="modal-target" data-modal-gallery="solutions">
          <img src="screenshot_package_tab.png" alt="x">
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <div class="cs-solution-head">
          <h3><span class="cs-solution-num">3 &middot;</span> Adoption guided by inventory readiness</h3>
          <p>Providers browsed pre-built packages instead of starting from a blank page. When adding a standard package, the system showed whether their inventory supported it and what was missing &mdash; shifting the question from &ldquo;what package should I invent?&rdquo; to &ldquo;which BabyQuip package can I support?&rdquo;</p>
        </div>
                <div class="modal-target" data-modal-gallery="solutions">
          <img src="screenshot_standardized_package_templates.png" alt="x">
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <div class="cs-solution-head">
          <h3><span class="cs-solution-num">4 &middot;</span> Legacy migration that protected provider work</h3>
          <p>Existing packages that matched a standard definition were converted into the standardized system &mdash; a custom bundle already containing the required crib, stroller, and toy categories mapped to the matching BabyQuip package. Anything that didn&rsquo;t match stayed as a custom package. No provider had to rebuild their work.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="modal-target" data-modal-gallery="solutions">
          <img src="screenshot_package_banner.png" alt="x">
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <div class="cs-solution-head">
          <h3><span class="cs-solution-num">5 &middot;</span> Lightweight consumer-facing representation</h3>
          <p>Because BabyQuip now controlled standard definitions, packages could be represented before provider selection for the first time. Exposure stayed intentionally lightweight: the system made early representation possible without over-promising availability before supply coverage could support it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="modal-target" data-modal-gallery="solutions">
          <img src="screenshot_shopping_page_package.png" alt="x">
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cs-callout-box">
      <div class="cs-callout-label">KEY CONSTRAINT &mdash; SUPPLY COVERAGE</div>
      <p class="cs-footnote-block cs-footnote-block--flush">Even with standard definitions, packages were still fulfilled by individual providers. A standard package only helped customers if enough providers in a market had adopted it with the required inventory. If promotion became dominant too early, customers could select a package and find no one able to fulfill it. <strong class="cs-text-emphasis">The design intentionally balanced future merchandising potential with current fulfillment reality.</strong></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="impact" class="cs-section cs-section--end container">
    <div class="cs-kicker">04 &mdash; IMPACT</div>
    <h2 class="cs-h2 cs-h2--narrow">A controlled, trackable package layer that can scale</h2>
    <p class="cs-lead">The project&rsquo;s impact was foundational rather than immediate conversion lift: it created the <strong class="cs-text-emphasis">operational and data layer</strong> needed to grow package adoption over time. The dashboards separated demand from adoption: with only ~28% of providers offering a standard package against clear bundle-like demand, BabyQuip could target adoption where demand already existed, then merchandise packages more confidently as coverage improves.</p>

    <div class="cs-two-col">
      <div>
        <div class="cs-subhead">What the system changed</div>
        <ul class="cs-list">
          <li>Inconsistent provider bundles &rarr; standardized, platform-defined packages</li>
          <li>Dedicated package area in the provider portal</li>
          <li>Matching legacy packages migrated; custom packages preserved</li>
          <li>Provider adoption became trackable, exposing supply gaps by market and package type</li>
          <li>The shopping flow can reference standard packages before provider selection</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="cs-subhead">What it makes possible next</div>
        <ul class="cs-list">
          <li>Package merchandising and seasonal bundle campaigns</li>
          <li>Market-level adoption targeting and provider education based on missing inventory</li>
          <li>Package recommendations based on customer trip needs</li>
          <li>Stronger availability logic and reliable bundle discovery as coverage improves</li>
        </ul>

      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="cs-subhead">Why supply came first</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">The visible consumer-facing change was only one part. The real design challenge was on the supply side &mdash; creating a structure that supports adoption, tracking, migration, and future merchandising. Consumer merchandising could only become reliable once the provider-side package model became standardized and trackable.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cs-pullquote">
      <p>Packages were flexible but fragmented: provider-specific upsells with no shared structure. Now they are <span class="accent">a platform-level system BabyQuip can define, track, migrate, and eventually merchandise</span>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

